<li><i><a href="/wiki/WarGames" title="WarGames">WarGames</a></i>, presented MAD by juxtaposing human fear with computed game theory</li>
<li><i><a href="/wiki/Defcon_(video_game)" title="Defcon (video game)">Defcon</a></i>, a video game where the player is on the cusp of MAD and must be careful not to provoke the enemy lest they achieve MAD</li>
<li><i><a href="/wiki/Veronica_Mars" title="Veronica Mars">Veronica Mars</a></i> had an episode during its first season in reference to mutual assured destruction called "<a href="/wiki/M.A.D._(Veronica_Mars)" title="M.A.D. (Veronica Mars)">M.A.D. (Veronica Mars)</a>".</li>
<li>In Chapter 38 of <i><a href="/wiki/White_Noise" title="White Noise" class="mw-redirect">White Noise</a></i>, a novel by Don DeLillo, "Mutual Assured Destruction" appears as part of a disembodied mantra: "Random Access Memory, Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome, Mutual Assured Destruction."</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Megadeth" title="Megadeth">Megadeth</a> song "Sweating Bullets" contains the line "Speak of mutually assured destruction? Nice story... tell it to <i>Readers Digest</i>!"</li>
</ul>
